1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
CueDeck has a free plan, a Pro plan,

2
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:10,300
and an Enterprise option.

3
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,225
It also has something a bit unusual:

4
00:00:13,525 --> 00:00:17,275
a per-event credit system for production teams who run events

5
00:00:17,575 --> 00:00:19,575
occasionally rather than continuously.

6
00:00:19,875 --> 00:00:23,625
In this episode I'll walk through all four options —

7
00:00:23,925 --> 00:00:26,550
what you get, what the limits are,

8
00:00:26,850 --> 00:00:29,100
when each one makes sense —

9
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:33,150
and I'll show you where to find your current usage

10
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:36,450
and how to upgrade directly from the console.

11
00:00:36,750 --> 00:00:40,125
There are three subscription plans and one credit option.

12
00:00:40,425 --> 00:00:43,800
Free gives you one active event at a time,

13
00:00:44,100 --> 00:00:46,725
up to five operators, two signage displays.

14
00:00:47,025 --> 00:00:49,275
No AI features, no post-event reports.

15
00:00:49,575 --> 00:00:52,575
It's enough to run your first event and

16
00:00:52,875 --> 00:00:55,125
evaluate whether CueDeck fits your workflow.

17
00:00:55,425 --> 00:00:58,050
No credit card required to sign up.

18
00:00:58,350 --> 00:01:00,350
Pro is €79 per month.

19
00:01:00,650 --> 00:01:02,900
Unlimited events, up to twenty operators,

20
00:01:03,200 --> 00:01:06,200
unlimited signage displays, full AI agent access —

21
00:01:06,500 --> 00:01:09,125
Incident Advisor, Cue Engine, Report Generator —

22
00:01:09,425 --> 00:01:11,425
and post-event report exports.

23
00:01:11,725 --> 00:01:15,100
This is the plan for teams running regular events:

24
00:01:15,400 --> 00:01:17,400
conferences, summits, roadshows, anything recurring.

25
00:01:17,700 --> 00:01:19,700
Enterprise is custom pricing.

26
00:01:19,1000 --> 00:01:22,250
Unlimited operators, dedicated support, custom onboarding,

27
00:01:22,550 --> 00:01:24,550
SLA agreements, and volume invoicing.

28
00:01:24,850 --> 00:01:28,600
If you're running large-scale events with 50-person production crews or

29
00:01:28,900 --> 00:01:31,525
you need a contract and procurement process,

30
00:01:31,825 --> 00:01:33,825
Enterprise is the path.

31
00:01:34,125 --> 00:01:36,125
And then there's Per-Event credit.

32
00:01:36,425 --> 00:01:40,175
This is for the production professional who runs two or

33
00:01:40,475 --> 00:01:43,475
three events a year — maybe a freelancer,

34
00:01:43,775 --> 00:01:46,775
maybe a team that handles occasional corporate events.

35
00:01:47,075 --> 00:01:49,325
You buy a single event credit,

36
00:01:49,625 --> 00:01:52,250
it unlocks Pro features for one event,

37
00:01:52,550 --> 00:01:55,925
and when that event ends the credit is consumed.

38
00:01:56,225 --> 00:01:58,225
No monthly commitment.

39
00:01:58,525 --> 00:02:02,275
Your current plan status is always one click away —

40
00:02:02,575 --> 00:02:04,575
in the user profile panel.

41
00:02:04,875 --> 00:02:07,500
Click your name chip in the header.

42
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:10,050
At the top of the panel:

43
00:02:10,350 --> 00:02:13,350
your name, your role, and a plan badge.

44
00:02:13,650 --> 00:02:17,025
If you're on Free it shows FREE in grey.

45
00:02:17,325 --> 00:02:19,325
Pro shows PRO in blue.

46
00:02:19,625 --> 00:02:21,625
Enterprise shows ENTERPRISE in purple.

47
00:02:21,925 --> 00:02:23,925
Below that, usage bars.

48
00:02:24,225 --> 00:02:27,975
If you're on the Free plan you can see exactly

49
00:02:28,275 --> 00:02:32,025
how many events you're using out of your one allowed.

50
00:02:32,325 --> 00:02:36,075
If you're on Pro the bars show operator count and

51
00:02:36,375 --> 00:02:38,375
display count versus your limits.

52
00:02:38,675 --> 00:02:40,925
These update in real time —

53
00:02:41,225 --> 00:02:44,225
as soon as you create an event or

54
00:02:44,525 --> 00:02:46,775
invite an operator, the bar adjusts.

55
00:02:47,075 --> 00:02:50,825
This is useful not just for tracking your own usage

56
00:02:51,125 --> 00:02:54,500
but for explaining your limits to a client or

57
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:57,050
a team member: 'we're on Free,

58
00:02:57,350 --> 00:03:01,100
we have one event — to run the second event

59
00:03:01,400 --> 00:03:03,400
we need to upgrade.'

60
00:03:03,700 --> 00:03:08,200
The Billing button inside the profile panel launches the Stripe checkout directly.

61
00:03:08,500 --> 00:03:11,500
CueDeck uses Stripe for all payment processing —

62
00:03:11,800 --> 00:03:15,550
it's the same payment infrastructure used by most major SaaS

63
00:03:15,850 --> 00:03:19,225
products, so your card details are handled by Stripe,

64
00:03:19,525 --> 00:03:21,525
not stored by CueDeck.

65
00:03:21,825 --> 00:03:25,200
On the checkout screen you'll see the plan options:

66
00:03:25,500 --> 00:03:28,125
Pro at €79 per month billed monthly,

67
00:03:28,425 --> 00:03:32,925
and Per-Event credit at the current per-event rate for a single-use unlock.

68
00:03:33,225 --> 00:03:36,600
Select your plan, enter your card details, and confirm.

69
00:03:36,900 --> 00:03:39,150
The upgrade is applied immediately —

70
00:03:39,450 --> 00:03:42,450
your plan badge in the profile panel updates,

71
00:03:42,750 --> 00:03:47,250
the usage limits change, and AI features unlock without a page refresh.

72
00:03:47,550 --> 00:03:50,550
CueDeck also supports VAT invoicing for European businesses.

73
00:03:50,850 --> 00:03:53,850
The checkout asks for your billing address and

74
00:03:54,150 --> 00:03:57,900
VAT number if applicable — invoices with proper VAT line

75
00:03:58,200 --> 00:04:00,450
items are generated automatically by Stripe.

76
00:04:00,750 --> 00:04:03,000
Once you're on a paid plan,

77
00:04:03,300 --> 00:04:07,050
the Manage Subscription link in the profile panel takes you

78
00:04:07,350 --> 00:04:09,350
to the Stripe customer portal.

79
00:04:09,650 --> 00:04:12,650
From there you can change your payment method,

80
00:04:12,950 --> 00:04:16,325
update your billing address, download past invoices as PDFs,

81
00:04:16,625 --> 00:04:18,625
or cancel your subscription.

82
00:04:18,925 --> 00:04:22,675
Invoice history is important for production companies billing clients —

83
00:04:22,975 --> 00:04:26,725
every monthly charge generates a proper Stripe invoice with a

84
00:04:27,025 --> 00:04:30,400
unique number, your billing address, and the line item.

85
00:04:30,700 --> 00:04:34,075
Download it, forward it to your accounts department, done.

86
00:04:34,375 --> 00:04:38,875
The practical decision tree: If you're just evaluating CueDeck — start Free.

87
00:04:39,175 --> 00:04:41,800
Sign up, create your event, run it,

88
00:04:42,100 --> 00:04:44,100
see if the workflow fits.

89
00:04:44,400 --> 00:04:46,400
No cost, no commitment.

90
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:48,950
If you run events regularly —

91
00:04:49,250 --> 00:04:53,000
monthly or more often, or multiple events per year with

92
00:04:53,300 --> 00:04:57,425
large crews — Pro at €79 a month is straightforward value.

93
00:04:57,725 --> 00:05:01,475
The AI agents alone justify it on any professional production.

94
00:05:01,775 --> 00:05:05,525
If you run one or two events a year and

95
00:05:05,825 --> 00:05:08,075
don't want a monthly subscription —

96
00:05:08,375 --> 00:05:10,625
Per-Event credit is built for you.

97
00:05:10,925 --> 00:05:13,175
Buy it when you need it,

98
00:05:13,475 --> 00:05:15,725
it unlocks for that event, and

99
00:05:16,025 --> 00:05:19,775
you're not paying €79 in the months you're not working.

100
00:05:20,075 --> 00:05:22,325
If you're an event management company,

101
00:05:22,625 --> 00:05:26,000
a large AV house, or you need procurement process,

102
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:30,050
SLA, or volume pricing — talk to the Enterprise team.

103
00:05:30,350 --> 00:05:33,350
There's a contact link on the pricing page.

104
00:05:33,650 --> 00:05:35,900
The pricing is designed so that

105
00:05:36,200 --> 00:05:38,200
the tool pays for itself.

106
00:05:38,500 --> 00:05:42,250
One session overrun caught early by the Cue Engine can

107
00:05:42,550 --> 00:05:44,800
save thirty minutes of programme time.

108
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:49,975
One well-written client debrief from the Report Generator can win the next contract.

109
00:05:50,275 --> 00:05:52,275
The numbers work.

110
00:05:52,575 --> 00:05:54,825
That's the full billing picture —

111
00:05:55,125 --> 00:05:57,750
Free for evaluation, Per-Event for occasional users,

112
00:05:58,050 --> 00:06:00,300
Pro for regular production teams, and

113
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:02,600
Enterprise for large organisations.

114
00:06:02,900 --> 00:06:06,275
Your usage is always visible in the profile panel,

115
00:06:06,575 --> 00:06:08,825
upgrading takes two minutes through Stripe,

116
00:06:09,125 --> 00:06:11,750
and you can download invoices any time.

117
00:06:12,050 --> 00:06:15,800
In the next episode we're going deep on multi-room and

118
00:06:16,100 --> 00:06:19,100
multi-track events — how to use room filters,

119
00:06:19,400 --> 00:06:21,650
the Programme signage view, anchor sessions,

120
00:06:21,950 --> 00:06:26,075
and how to run a three-track conference without losing your mind.

121
00:06:26,375 --> 00:06:28,375
I'll see you there.
